## The short answer

Stop opening with “Anything for me?” Explain what the one-on-one is for, share questions in advance, ask about a specific horizon, and tolerate the pause. Let the direct report use most of the time, but do not make them responsible for inventing a useful meeting from nothing.

## When this guidance fits

Use this when the one-on-one is recurring and the person consistently has no agenda or gives one-word answers. Consider language, neurodiversity, remote context, seniority, and whether your previous responses taught them that candor is costly.

> **Stop and get support:** if the person raises harassment, discrimination, health, safety, retaliation, or another formal concern, explain the limits of confidentiality and use the correct support process. Do not promise to keep serious issues “just between us.”

## 1 — See

Look at the meeting design before judging engagement. Is the time predictable? Who talks more? Do you turn every concern into an assignment, rebuttal, or status interrogation? Are your questions answerable with “fine”? Notice whether silence changes when the topic is future work, energy, friction, growth, or your own support.

## 2 — Choose

Reset the purpose and provide scaffolding. Try a short menu of questions sent a day ahead. Use one follow-up instead of six rapid prompts. If trust is low, consistency and follow-through will do more than a clever question list.

## 3 — Say

> “I’ve noticed I often ask what you want to cover and put you on the spot. This time is for your work experience, risks, growth, and anything I can clarify or unblock—not a status report. I’ll send two questions before we meet. For today: what has taken more energy than it should this week?”

If they still say nothing: “Okay. I’ll give us a quiet minute. You can also choose: workload, team friction, growth, or something you need from me.”

## If they respond with…

### “Everything is fine.”

Ask for variation, not a hidden problem: “What felt easiest this week? What felt needlessly hard?”

### “I don’t know what you want me to say.”

Own the ambiguity: “There is no answer I am looking for. Let me explain how I use what you tell me and where confidentiality has limits.”

### “Can we skip these?”

Ask what has made them low-value. Keep the recurring relationship space, but adjust format, cadence, or preparation based on what you learn.

## 4 — Sustain

Protect the next three meetings, send one or two prompts in advance, and follow through on any manager commitment. Keep brief notes about promises, not a secret dossier. Revisit whether the format is becoming more useful after a month.

